name: Washington Park Stunning Townhouse
description:
Beautiful Townhouse located blocks to Washington Park (Wash Park) quick and easy access to downtown.



Easy walk to Light Rail, Whole foods and park. Amazing property with great deck with Mtn views. Attached Garage, interior is spectacular. Great place to get away in Denver and enjoy the park and the city.
neighborhood_overview:
ABOUT THE NEIGHBORHOOD/LOCATION:

- Its Wash Park – just look up wash park and Denver and you will get lot of information for this location.

- It is a premier location for the city, with great access to Denver’s most highly rated park, easy access to downtown and Cherry Creek.

- Restaurants, bars and other stores very close, but not close enough to affect noise or any level of inconvenience or crime.

TRANSPORTATION & PARKING:
- Light Rail is 3 blocks away and run’s directly downtown in less than 15 mins or to DTC in less than 15 mins.

- Walk (or run around) fabulous Wash Park – only blocks away

- Easy to get to the house from the airport, easy to locate.

- There is an attached 1.5 Car Garage in the bottom of the house, for 1 car. Additional parking is easy to find and free on the street.

- Very close to other great destinations, like Platt park, Sushi Den and other great restaurants, bars
host_about: Originally from UK, love Colorado, hiking mtn biking and Skiing.

name: Private room in the nest - w/bathroom
description: Private small room with own bath on the 2nd floor of a historic building in Baker. Walkable to 5 different coffee shops, shopping, theater, bars, galleries, ice cream, restaurants, distilleries & breweries. All the toast and jam you can eat. This is a cozy internationally influenced home in Denver with a long time Denver resident host. I am an entrepreneur, artist and traveler. I love meeting and hosting guests, but also can give you plenty of space. There is a large but sweet dog in the home.
neighborhood_overview:
The place is in Baker District, within walking distance is the Santa Fe Arts district and the south Broadway district.

The Santa Fe arts district to the west has 1st Friday events, many many galleries, several breweries and a few very good Mexican Restaurants, one of which has one of the best patios in Denver, El Noa Noa, and the other, El Tacos de Mexico, just won a James Beard award for classic places.

To the east is the South Broadway area which is filled with shopping, restaurants, bars, a vintage movie theater, ice cream, salons, Walgreens, a yoga studio, thrift stores, coffee shops, book stores & several breweries. Restaurants range from pizza by the slice, to a few notable dining establishments that won’t disappoint.

There is also a rec center 1 block away with a swimming pool, weight machines and basket ball courts that one can purchase limited use passes to. Across the street is a city park with a playground and basketball courts and lots
host_about: Small business owner of a unique company that celebrates the spirit of travel & picnicking called RedCamper. Love food, dogs, hikes in the foothills at dusk and a well made cocktail. I've been in Denver since 1999 so I know a few things to see and do.

name: Super-comfortable Modern Home 3 Bdr -Platt Park DU
description: Beautifully renovated 1800 s/f home. Contemporary architecture in a comfortable, open setting. Great light, chef's kitchen, comfy beds and nicer amenities. We are close to Steam Espresso, Platt Park Brewing, Sushi Den, Kaos Pizza, Old Pearl Street and DU/University of Denver - great for 1, 2 or 3 couples, families, and business travelers.
neighborhood_overview: Platt Park is a like a beautiful small town within the confines of our gorgeous and dynamic Denver, Colorado.
host_about: My wife Vicki and I have lived in Denver since the early 1980's (Vicki's from Iowa, I'm from West Texas). We love anything outdoors - mountain biking, camping, canoeing and scuba diving/beach-bumming :) We're foodies- Asian, sushi, great pizza, and Mexican in particular. We are coffee fanatics - I make espresso most every day and roast the beans occasionally.  We are accomplished cooks who enjoy entertaining, and appreciate good wine. We also enjoy great music - we're regulars at the Telluride Bluegrass Festival and Red Rocks concerts and especially love live music. And we love being airbnb hosts! Because of airbnb we have met the most amazing, delightful and diverse group of people imaginable.

name: Private apt in Berkeley, MTN Views!
neighborhood_overview: Our homes are situated in the Berkeley neighborhood which is filled with beautiful parks,  lovely vistas, exceptionally outstanding restaurants and charming boutiques. This is a park like property with lots of room and every space on Airbnb has a private entrance,  bathing facilities and cooking facilities.   It is also very easy to access all the practical services from grocery stores to hairdressers  to cleaners to beauty treatments,  yoga and pet services. name: Modern Guest House in Berkeley Lake
description: Just a few blocks away from great restaurants, bars, shops, parks and even a lake, this airy, well appointed guest cottage is a cozy spot to enjoy our amazing city and neighborhood. Come visit the mile high city and relax at night in our quiet urban casita. With easy access to I-70, this is also a great jumping off place to explore the mountains.
neighborhood_overview:
Our neighborhood is great. And only getting better! It's set out far enough from downtown that driving and parking isn't an issue, but it's still only a 10 min ride/cab ride to all downtown has to offer. It has it's own vibrant shop/restaurant district called Tennyson st with great coffee shops, tons of restaurants--and more opening every month. Sprouts grocery store that is a 5 minute walk from the house. We also have a beautiful lake and park a couple blocks away that offers great views of the mountains and a nice path if you want to go for a run. We are located only 5 minutes off I-70 so it's nearly a straight shot to get up into the mountains.
In the summer, you can walk from the house to Lakeside Amusement Park, one of the old-style amusement parks with wooden roller coasters where you pay per ride for a fun, nostalgic afternoon.
host_about: Carlos and I have both lived in Denver for over 10 years and we love this city. We have 2 dogs and you will often find us at a local restaurant/bar, the park or even just in the backyard spending time with the pups and our family. We enjoy the outdoors and we love the easy access to skiing and hiking that Denver provides as well as the young, active, friendly vibe of the people here. We look forward to meeting travelers and helping them feel as comfortable and at home as possible here in Denver. We also love traveling and really getting to know the areas that we visit including the people and culture of new cities. Airbnb provides a way to immediately immerse yourself in a new place and we love that.

name: Room Upstairs @ Eric's HipFunPad
description: A sweet pad located on Tennyson St in one of Denver's hottest neighborhoods with restaurants, breweries, bars, shops, coffee and parks within 6 blocks. This is a shared apartment above the owner’s e-bike shop. I sleep in the upstairs master bedroom, but you’ll only see me coming and going since I practically live in my bike shop downstairs.  Just over 3 miles to downtown. Upstairs at Eric's is relaxing with a covered patio, great sound system, chalk wall, movie projector, drum kit + more.
neighborhood_overview: There is hardly any reason to leave the neighborhood if you don't want to. This house is right on charming Tennyson Street - almost a mile long thriving cultural district with a wide variety of bars, coffee shops, restaurants, art galleries, live music venues, shops, parks and less than a block away from a Natural Foods grocery store.  There are four restaurants on this stretch listed on Westword's "100 Restaurants We Can't Live Without" issue.
host_about: I work in live entertainment production and have lived in Denver for nearly 30 years.  Most of that time in the house in my listing.  The house is a 1893 duplex built with an upstairs, 2 floor apartment and a main floor apartment.  I used to rent out the downstairs apartment, but now I live down there and only use the upstairs apartment when it's not rented out here.  My first drum kit is upstairs, and it's still my favorite of all I have owned.  Feel free to use it if you rent the Upstairs@ Erics listing.  I also rent out a private room in my main floor apartment which is shared full time with me.  Bicycles are my other passion and I enjoy converting regular bikes to electric bikes in a part time business I run from my front room.  Ask me about ebike rentals or tours! I really do enjoy sharing my comfortable space with people from all over the world on AirBnB.

name: GARDEN SUITE: COMFORT & BEAUTY IN AN HISTORIC HOME
description:
THE BEAUTIFUL, UPDATED Garden Suite is a perfect retreat for a traveler, parent, doctor/ intern, or an executive. It is private, secure & well managed, with 2 private entries. Nestled in our 1912 Arts and Crafts home, this apartment is open & spacious with comfy, elegant furnishings. A gas stove in the living room warms up wintry evenings.
We are a mature couple preferring a tranquil environment, so we seek an individual who shares these values. All is provided -Just bring a suitcase!
neighborhood_overview:
We are 10 minutes due east of downtown traveling by car on 17th Street. Directly to the west is the lovely Johnson and Wales campus just two blocks away, and Park Hill, one of Denver's oldest and most elegant neighborhoods is also to the west. Park Hill features some lovely parkways, including 17th Street, Montview Boulevard, 23rd Street and Monaco Boulevard; it is a nice place to walk. (And if you're really motivated, the Zoo, City Park and Museum of Nature and Science are about 2.5 miles west.)
To the north and south are the relatively newer neighborhoods of Stapleton and Lowry, with town centers, restaurants and cafes.
Going to the east, the neighborhoods are more transitional, but changing fast as they are now anchored by the newer and huge Anshutz Medical Campus. Not to be missed is the spanking new Stanley Marketplace, housed in a former airplane factory, with brewpubs and some of the most innovative new restaurants in Denver. I-70, the main route to the mountains
host_about:
Hello, thanks for taking the time to read about us.  I came from the beautiful Finger Lakes area in upstate New York, moving here at 18 years old because I "had never known until I came to Colorado that the sun could come out in winter. "  That being the case, of course I never left. Lynne is from Colorado, with great-grandparents who grew up in Georgetown and old Snowmass. Life back then was not glamorous and a living was cobbled together from gritty pursuits such as silver mining.  
We love beautiful spaces, the outdoors, art in its many forms, and the company of good friends.  One of our careers together has been restoring neglected historic homes, and our home has been an almost two-decades long work in progress.  Restoring the apartment was one of our earlier efforts, and as is usually the case, we found architectural clues as to what our home's earlier owners had been up to.  (Such as the enormous beams that proved the claim that our house had been moved from Denver Municipal Airport in 1928. That airport became the old Stapleton Airport. We also heard from a gentleman in his ninties that he had watched it being moved.)
We believe historic homes are living history, in real time.  Having modern amenities makes them all the more appealing.
Possibly our greatest love is travel.  We agree with St. Gus, who said "The world is a book, and those who do not travel read only one page." And of course our favorite part of traveling is and always will be connecting with people from all walks of life, from all around the world. We're so thankful to have the opportunity to do this once more through hosting. 
Wishing you safe and happy travels!

name: Bright Sunny Fourplex Unit in Clayton Neighborhood
description:
Have a bright, recently-updated row house (one unit in a quadplex building) all to yourself in Denver's historic Clayton Neighborhood. Quiet and residential, but still close to the heart of the city.

This unit is furnished ideally for a couple where one or both of you are working from home. Airy and colorful decor includes contemporary touches, local fine art pieces, and antique heirloom details. I go for a clean, minimalist vibe.
neighborhood_overview:
Some quotes on Clayton from Urbanist Insider:
"All in all, Clayton rocks because of its proximity to everywhere else in Denver, without being a busy thoroughfare. Neighbors are friendly and likely to greet you as you walk down the street. Parking is always available. Sirens are not common, and most cars drive safely through the ‘hood. The disadvantage to Clayton is that it’s so darn residential. Without much to walk to, you will definitely want to consider having a car to get around. Busses come down the major streets and bikes are certainly an option -- but having your own vehicle would be preferable here. If you don’t mind the quiet, check out Clayton."

There's not much in close proximity as far as local eateries or grocery stores, but I do recommend Lucero's down the street for fab burritos and green chili, and the tamales at Tres Girasoles are also bomb.
host_about:
Hi! I'm a Denver native and full-time marketing manager. When not working, I love getting outside in Colorado.

I bought this house in 2017 and lived here solo for five years. In 2022 I moved in with my fiancee (less than a mile away!) and I'm excited to rent it out furnished month-to-month to traveling medical staff or professionals working remotely. 

As a lifelong Denverite, I know more than most about the Mile High City! Just ask =)

name: Historic, Artsy 2 story house in the Heart of RiNo
description:
Enjoy the best of Denver in the heart of the vibrant RiNo neighborhood in our circa 1890 two story brick home. Artistically decorated and stocked with amenities for your friends and family. One block from coffee shops, restaurants, breweries, shopping and live music. Two very large and two small bedrooms sleeps at least 7, fenced in backyard and key-less check-in.

neighborhood_overview:
This is a walking/biking neighborhood. Just about anything you need is within a few minutes stroll. That said, parking can be hard to come by streetside on the weekends, but readily available within a block or two anytime. Uber/Lyft/Taxi's are recommended over a rental car. If you do have a car, we have a parking pass for the block in front of the house but it absolutely must be returned upon checkout, they are hard to get re-issued!
We are in the city! The neighborhood is a mix of residents who are third and fourth generation, new additions to the hip new restaurant and art scene as well as a fair number of Denver's transient/vagrant population- as is the case with most larger cities in this day and age. We haven't had any safety issues at the house, but please use common sense and keep doors locked and gates closed. Also, we encourage not leaving anything in vehicles.

neighborhood_overview: Berkeley is a city-center neighborhood in Denver, Colorado, located in the area traditionally called Northwest Denver on the west side of Interstate 25 and just south of Interstate 70. The neighborhood is bounded by Federal Boulevard on the east, I-70 on the north, Sheridan Boulevard on the West and 38th avenue on the south. It is bordered by the West Highland neighborhood on the south and is often erroneously grouped together with the Highlands. The neighborhood contains two lakes surrounded by parks, one eponymous (stretching from 46th Avenue to I-70 and Sheridan Boulevard to Tennyson Street) and Rocky Mountain Lake Park (stretching from Lowell Boulevard to Grove Street and 46th Avenue to I-70). Berkeley Park also contains the William Scheitler Recreation Center, run by the City and County of Denver and including both indoor and outdoor public pools. name: Old Skool Unique Renovated Liquor Store!
description: Welcome to an old Denver staple, the world famous (haha) Cut Rate Liquor store!! Built in 1874 but completely renovated and happily unique, just a little bit weird. neighborhood_overview:
Very Urban, but safe and close to lots of city things. I've lived in this neighborhood for 23 years, this is real Denver in a real neighborhood, if you want an authentic experience in a mixed residential neighborhood, here ya go. My lady Cathy is like 5' tall (you'd never guess from talking to her on the phone, ahem) she loves walking around with me, exploring and meeting the neighbors near and far on a pleasant summer night. If it's cold she yells at me a lot lol.

It's amazing, very walkable (6-10 blocks depending on which direction) to dozens of restaurants and bars. My favorite bar is two blocks away. Light rail is a block and a half away, cheap RTD/ Uber to everything in the city. Denver Center for the Performing Arts is easily accessible from transit, as are a dozen concert and show venues like the Odgen, the Bluebird, Mission Ballroom and the Fillmore. Uber is usually cheap because you'll be so central. The interstate is like 6 minutes away. It's in the middle of an a
host_about:

Join me and let's smile!

Thanks for considering my place, have safe and amazing travels!

name: PRIVATE Home, Yard and Garage in Trendy District
description:
Walk to one of Denver’s hippest areas—RiNo art district—from this beautifully renovated historic home. This area boasts a heavy concentration of breweries, coffee shops, restaurants, music halls and art venues, and is known for its colorful street art.
Convenient to the light rail station, which takes you to Union Station or the airport! Minutes from downtown Denver, City Park, zoo and science museum. Ideal place for a long term stay. Owner has 12+yrs of Denver experience to share with you!
neighborhood_overview: A historic and vibrant city neighborhood with ample street parking. RiNo district is considered one of the most economically and racially diverse neighborhoods in Denver, and it is quickly evolving due to the influx of tourism to RiNo Art District (a conglomerate of 4 historic neighborhoods, including Cole/this one). We have great neighbors on the block that we have a strong rapport with. I’ve lived here for 6 years and love it! You’ll love it too! However, if city life and associated noise isn’t for you then please consider booking elsewhere.
host_about: Hello! I’m a Wyoming native, claiming CO home since 2007. My husband, daughter, son and I are outdoor enthusiasts. We live in the Rocky Mountains west of Denver and short term rent our Denver home. My travel style tends to be "on the fly". I love booking a flight with lots of time and few plans. I'm a runner, skier, mtn biker and lover of the outdoors and exploration. Thank you for hosting me, my friends and family so that we can explore a new place.

name: Gorgeous Historic Loft in LoDo w/ 77" OLED screen!
description: Welcome to my historic loft! Boasting a stunning, state-of-the-art 77" LG C1 TV screen with Sonos Arc sound bar as a centerpiece, this quiet, sparkling-clean gem is the perfect place for a staycation, an extended stay, or a romantic getaway; and an ideal haven to unwind, work away from home, watch movies, or find inspiration for your thesis or novel. This uniquely designed, fully upgraded open loft (with gym + gated, covered parking)  is located between Coors Field and the Platte River walk!
host_about:
Hi! My name is Alexandre. I am a spirited and adventurous documentary filmmaker and comic book writer, originally from Geneva, Switzerland. My last three films -- "78/52: Hitchcock's Shower Scene" ; "Memory: The Origins of Alien" ; and "Leap of Faith: William Friedkin on The Exorcist" -- premiered at the Sundance Film Festival in 2017, 2019, and 2020, respectively. 78/52 is now available on Hulu and Blu Ray/DVD; and Memory is also available on Blu Ray/DVD and on most digital platforms. Leap of Faith is currently streaming on Shudder. My latest film, Lynch/Oz, just premiered at the Tribeca Film Festival in June!

I'm currently working on several exciting feature projects, and always traveling as a result. This is why I choose to make my home available to fellow travelers. I am driven by mindfulness, integrity, kindness, empathy, childlike curiosity, an endless fascination for this extraordinary world we live in, and a passion for creative expression. 

If you like watching docs, you may have come across some of my other titles on Netflix or Hulu: The People vs. George Lucas, Doc of the Dead, The Life and Times of Paul the Psychic Octopus, etc. 

I have lived in Switzerland, France, England (Dorset, to be exact), Zimbabwe (Harare), San Diego, San Francisco, NYC (college years), and now Denver. I’m crazy about Northern California, the Pacific Northwest, and New Zealand... and will probably be visiting one of said places while you're enjoying my loft! ;)

I'm a huge movie buff, and my new loft has just been fully upgraded with a state-of-the-art LG C1 OLED 77" screen with Sonos sound bar! So you'll have your own mini movie theater right inside your home away from home!

Favorite filmmakers: David Lynch, William Wyler, Alfred Hitchcock, Mikio Naruse, Akira Kurosawa, Kiyoshi Kurosawa, Sergio Leone, Ingmar Bergman, Wes Anderson, Stanley Kubrick, David Lean, Orson Welles, John Huston, Josef von Sternberg, Michelangelo Antonioni, P.T. Anderson, Joel & Ethan Coen... okay, I'm going to stop here.

Films I couldn't do without: Vertigo, Strangers on a Train, Psycho, Mulholland Drive, Seven Samurai, Rushmore, Woman in the Dunes, The Shining, Citizen Kane, The Assassination of Jesse James by the Coward Robert Ford, Blade Runner, Star Wars, The Big Sleep, The Killing, Nosferatu, Fargo, and... The Good, The Bad & The Ugly.

neighborhood_overview:
In 1878, the American circus mogul P.T. Barnum of the Barnum and Bailey Circus bought 760 acres for just $11,000, and a few years later, the Barnum subdivision was platted.

Barnum's involvement with his namesake's development has become part of Denver folklore, especially in the durable legend of the showman's plan to establish a winter home for his circus in the city. In fact, Barnum never wintered his animals anywhere other than Connecticut or Florida, and the entertainment entrepreneur made just four documented trips to Colorado. Barnum sold as much of Barnum as possible before disposing of the remainder to his daughter, Helen Buchtel, for the price of one dollar. Ironically, much of Barnum's initial development was a result of efforts by Helen, and her second husband, William Buchtel, who also served as mayor of an independent, incorporated Barnum established in 1887

Walking distance to: the light rail, Little Man Ice Cream, Sloan's Lake, Meow Wolf, Brew Culture Coffee, dispensaries, Alamo Craft House Cinema, and more.

Soak in Denver with the privacy of a space to call your home away from home.
neighborhood_overview:
Sloan's lake is one of the best located and iconic places in Denver. With being close to the city you can take advantage of everything Denver has to offer without feeling like you are stuck in the hustle and bustle of city life. Start your morning off skiing Loveland with the locals, come back for some ice cream at Little Man Ice Cream up the street, then take the light rail or an Uber for a short ride to downtown for a night in the city. Or, if your not up to it, you can just walk up the street to any one of the trendy brews like the Alamo (maybe even catch a movie). If you're here for work, you can start your day with a walk to Starbucks (or a microbrew coffee joint if you're up for it), come back and work in your private space, take a walk to the light rail to catch a meeting and swing back for a nice night out in Edgewater (just a short uber away).

The possibilities are endless with this prime location.

neighborhood_overview:
In 1878, the American circus mogul P.T. Barnum of the Barnum and Bailey Circus bought 760 acres for just $11,000, and a few years later, the Barnum subdivision was platted.

Barnum's involvement with his namesake's development has become part of Denver folklore, especially in the durable legend of the showman's plan to establish a winter home for his circus in the city. In fact, Barnum never wintered his animals anywhere other than Connecticut or Florida, and the entertainment entrepreneur made just four documented trips to Colorado. Barnum sold as much of Barnum as possible before disposing of the remainder to his daughter, Helen Buchtel, for the price of one dollar. Ironically, much of Barnum's initial development was a result of efforts by Helen, and her second husband, William Buchtel, who also served as mayor of an independent, incorporated Barnum established in 1887

neighborhood_overview: The River North Art District "where art is made" goes by the nickname of "RiNo" and has even adopted a rhino design for its official logo, so look for creative rhinos in art and signage all around the neighborhood! The district's interesting blend of urban charm and unique industrial revival makes it a great destination for visitors. Historic warehouses and factories now house jazz bars, restaurants, brewpubs, art galleries and working studios. RiNo boasts a diverse mix of creative businesses ranging from visual artists, designers and furniture makers, to craft distillers and brewers, winemakers, creators of unique outdoor gear and small-batch coffee roasters. The art definitely extends beyond gallery walls in this neighborhood, with its colorful and innovative street art murals in alleys and on buildings around almost every corner!

neighborhood_overview:
We live on a residential street with ample street parking in a safe and conveniently located neighborhood. There is easy walking, biking, bus, and driving access to all the city has to offer.

Cherry Creek North (8 minute walk) has the city's highest concentration of locally-owned stores. It has 65 restaurants, numerous art galleries, fashion boutiques, home furnishings stores and a multitude of spas, salons and fitness studios nestled along charming tree-lined streets. It is also the location for the Cherry Creek Arts Festival, a free 3 day festival when the neighborhood transforms itself into one of the largest outdoor galleries, treating visitors to live music, performance art, food and fun.

Denver Botanic Gardens (15 minute walk) has a wide range of beautiful gardens, highlighting Colorado's native plants and showcasing plants from around the globe.
